// Mesopotamian gods — the 12 canonical deities of Sumer / Akkad / Babylon /
// Assyria — SEO funnel. /gab44/mesopotamian-gods (index) + /gab44/mesopotamian-gods/{slug}.
//
// The seventh great pantheon on gab44 after Olympians, Norse, Hindu Devas,
// Egyptian, Celtic, and Orishas. The OLDEST written religion on the site
// (clay-tablet attestation from c. 3000 BCE Sumer) — and the *literal source*
// of zodiac astrology (the 12-sign Babylonian zodiac, codified in the
// MUL.APIN tablets c. 1000 BCE, is what every modern western horoscope is
// downstream of) and the *literal source* of the 7-classical-planet system
// (Shamash = Sun, Sin = Moon, Nabu = Mercury, Ishtar = Venus, Nergal = Mars,
// Marduk = Jupiter, Ninurta = Saturn — the seven Babylonian planet-deities
// became the seven Greco-Roman ones became our seven weekday-names).
//
// Three families × 4 deities:
//  - Foundational Triad + Chaos (Anu/Enlil/Enki/Tiamat — sky-father /
//    storm-king / water-wisdom / primordial-salt-sea-chaos — the
//    cosmogonic-foundational layer of the Enuma Elish).
//  - Bright Heavens (Shamash/Sin/Inanna-Ishtar/Marduk — sun-of-justice /
//    moon-of-Ur / Venus-love-and-war / Jupiter-king-of-Babylon — the
//    radiant-visible-sky layer).
//  - Far Travelers & Underworld (Nergal/Nabu/Ninurta/Ereshkigal — Mars /
//    Mercury / Saturn / Pluto — the planetary-traveler layer plus the
//    queen-of-the-underworld).
//
// Source-honest from the Enuma Elish (the Babylonian creation epic c. 1100
// BCE on 7 tablets, the canonical Marduk-defeats-Tiamat narrative), the
// Epic of Gilgamesh (the Standard Babylonian Version c. 1300-1000 BCE on
// 12 tablets — the world's first epic, predating Homer by 1500 years),
// the Descent of Inanna to the Underworld (Sumerian c. 1900 BCE — the
// foundational dying-and-rising-goddess narrative that predates every
// Greek/Christian parallel by millennia), the MUL.APIN astronomical
// compendium c. 1000 BCE (the literal source-document of the 12-sign
// zodiac), the Code of Hammurabi c. 1754 BCE (under the patronage of
// Shamash), the Atra-Hasis flood-epic c. 1700 BCE, the Hymns of Enheduanna
// c. 2300 BCE (the world's first named author — daughter of Sargon of
// Akkad, high-priestess of Inanna at Ur), Stephanie Dalley's *Myths from
// Mesopotamia* (Oxford World's Classics 1989/2000 — the canonical
// English-language anthology), Thorkild Jacobsen's *The Treasures of
// Darkness* (Yale 1976 — the foundational interpretive monograph), Samuel
// Noah Kramer's *History Begins at Sumer* (1956), Jean Bottéro's
// *Religion in Ancient Mesopotamia* (Chicago 2001), Andrew George's
// edition of the Epic of Gilgamesh (Penguin 1999), and the cuneiform
// tablets in the British Museum, the Louvre, the Vorderasiatisches
// Museum Berlin, and the Iraq Museum Baghdad.
//
// Shadow-honest: the 19th-c. Assyriologist-orientalist framing that
// presented Mesopotamian religion as "pagan precursor to be superseded
// by Israelite monotheism" (the Genesis-flood-as-corrected-Atra-Hasis,
// the Tower-of-Babel-as-polemic-against-ziggurats, the Babylon-as-
// whore-of-Revelation tradition); the silent extraction of the Code-of-
// Hammurabi into Mosaic-law and of the Atra-Hasis-flood into the Noah
// narrative and of the Gilgamesh-Utnapishtim into Noah-and-Methuselah
// without source-acknowledgment until 1872 (George Smith's reading of
// the flood-tablet at the British Museum) and even then resisted by
// fundamentalist scholarship for another century; the catastrophic
// 2003 Iraq Museum looting that destroyed irreplaceable Mesopotamian
// material culture during the US invasion of Iraq (the Warka Mask of
// Inanna was recovered but the Babylonian boundary stones and many
// cuneiform tablets are still missing); the 2014-2017 ISIS destruction
// of Nimrud, Hatra, and Nineveh which deliberately targeted Assyrian
// religious sites; the modern "ancient aliens" / History-Channel
// pseudoarchaeology that has appropriated the Anunnaki name into a
// Zecharia-Sitchin-derived UFO-mythology entirely unconnected to actual
// Mesopotamian theology; the colonial-museum question of who owns the
// Ishtar Gate (currently in the Pergamon Museum Berlin) and the
// Cyrus Cylinder (British Museum) and whether they should return to
// Iraq and Iran respectively; the modern feminist-spirituality
// flattening of Inanna into a generic "goddess archetype" that strips
// the historical complexity of her war-goddess-as-much-as-love-goddess
// register; the white-nationalist co-option of Sumerian motifs by
// 1990s-2020s far-right NeoPagan / Theosophical / esoteric-Aryan
// circles that have invented entire false-Sumerian theological systems.

